(e) Using the full data set, investigate the predictors graphcially, using scatterplots or other tools of your choice. Create some plots highlighting the relationships among the predictors. Comment on your findings.

e-1) relationship between displacement and mpg
dis = Auto$displacement
mpg = Auto$mpg

plot(dis, mpg, xlab="displacement", ylab="mpg")

As displacement increases, there is a tendency for mpg to decrease. Displacement and mpg have a negative correlation.

e-2) relationship between displacement and horsepower
dis = Auto$displacement
horsepower = Auto$horsepower

plot(dis, horsepower, xlab="displacement", ylab="horsepower")

When displacement increases, we can observe an increase in horsepower as well. These two variables have a positive correlation.

e-3) relationship between horsepower and cylinder

horsepower = Auto$horsepower
cylinder = Auto$cylinders

plot(cylinder, horsepower, xlab="cylinder", ylab="horsepower")

When cylinder increases, we can observe an increase in horsepower as well. These two variables have a positive correlation.

(f) Suppose that we wish to predict gas mileage (mpg) on the basis of the other variables. Do your plots suggest that any of the other variables might be useful in predicting mpg? Justify your answer.

From the scatter plot(e-1) above, we can observe a strong correlation between displacement and mpg. Therefore, it can be inferred that other variables are useful in predicting mpg.

(c) Are any of the predictors associated with per capita crime rate? If so, explain the relationship.

crim = Boston$crim
chas = Boston$chas

stripchart(crim ~ factor(chas), xlab="chas", ylab="crime" ,vertical=TRUE)

It can be seen that the crime rate per capita is significantly higher in the case where it is not located at the boundary of the river than in the case where it is located at the boundary of the river.
